Feeling overwhelmed? You are not alone. Happy to share with all of you an original song about experiencing mental health struggles. It’s the Caroline Dare story, but I hope it resonates with all of you who are dealing with the same thing. You are loved and supported!

We are here for you. 🤍

May is Mental Health Awareness month. 
“Where I used to be” is an extremely relatable song when it comes to our mental health journeys. 
One day at a time. Be proud of the progress you make. Although you may not be where you want to be right now be gracious to God you’re not where you used to be. I hope this song finds you at a time when you need it the most. Keep going. 

Thank you so much to our friend @carolinedaremusic for not only repping our shirt but for always making the time to show our community love and support. Glad to have you as an ambassador for mental health. 

#mentalhealthawarenessmonth

thank you so much for all the love on M.I.A.🕊️ i wrote the song after learning one of the biggest lessons in my adult life so far: setting boundaries for myself & protecting my peace.
i’ve picked up on a reoccurring theme throughout my life where i would find myself bending over backwards & over-compromising for people who would not reciprocate or meet me where i was. i felt responsible for things i shouldn’t have been responsible for. it brought me a lot of stress because i was trying to control & correct things that i simply just couldn’t. it drained me. & i knew it wasn’t what i deserved, but i accepted it because it was all i knew at the time. my voice was often overpowered & dismissed whenever i expressed my feelings, so i shut down over time. i dismissed my own needs to everyone.
i do not tolerate that treatment anymore. i’ve learned it’s okay to say no to people & to things you don’t wanna do. you don’t have to hold onto old friendships or relationships that only drain you or add stress to your life. it’s okay to distance yourself & let go of people who only want to hold onto you for their own benefit.
i grew up thinking that everyone else’s needs were above my own & i’ve been in relationships where i put the other person on a pedestal above me. but i know now that it wasn’t fair to myself. & if someone’s not giving you what you what you truly deserve & they’re not willing to hear you out & work with you on it, so be it. you know there’s better for you.
keep thriving, stay grateful, prioritize your wellbeing. you’ll see tremendous amounts of your own growth while reluctant people will remain stuck in the same place.
& they don’t need to hear from you either. don’t keep feeding into it. as long as you keep showing up for yourself, you cannot be ignored.

“be kind & forgiving when no one else will; happiness will find your heart again. again & again.”🕊️
mark, i am so devastated i never got to say goodbye to you or get coffee together one last time. we talked about it many times but it never came about, & i didn’t realize the last time i was ever going to see you again was back in july.
knowing you was such a blessing & you made a tremendous impact on me, more than you’ll ever know. the efforts & strides you made to progress the mental health community hold immense magnitude & will forever continue to. it has been a beautiful experience watching you help so many struggling people, including traumatized veterans & adolescent psych patients. just by being as genuine as you are. a multifaceted songwriter, social worker, author, volunteer, etc. thank you for always holding a safe space for me even though you were not feeling your best & things were difficult. thank you for letting me be part of your creative journey. thank you for including me in a chapter of the book you were in the process of publishing. thank you for teaching me how to check the oil level in my car. thank you for sharing your vibrant life experiences with me & openly offering your insight & advice. sharing the stage with you over the past 3 years has been an honor, to say the least.
i will never forget the kindness you spread & the care you gave to those around you. i hope you knew how loved you are. thank you for caring for the stray dog we rescued from the street & providing him the most loving home. you truly have always been a mentor & like family to me. losing you is such a heavy loss. your lyrics have always been so heartfelt - your music will continue to stay here & i am so grateful i will always have that to hold onto.
mark, i will never take these memories with you for granted. you are so close to my heart & i wish there was more i could’ve done to be there for you. witnessing the decline of your health was shattering & excruciating. but i’m hoping your spirit is at peace & you’re not too far away. i’ll be looking out for you always 🤍 rest easy mark i love you

2023 has been an expansive year for my music, i put out 2 CDs - one being an entirely self produced album, released my first vinyl, created different drastic visuals for each of my singles with my best friend, did my first feature on a song, played a few fulfilling shows, & geez that’s not even all of it! & im ending the year by putting out “weaning” on friday, which i think is a good way to close the chapter.
thank you for supporting me this year! i’m already working so hard for 2024 to be my biggest year yet🤍

“weaning” is out now🕊️
produced by me !!
written by me & @luisawilsonmusic !!
this song really reflects my own personal growth over the past 2 years. it’s my closure & clarity, the reassurance i needed & a reconnection to my identity.
the idea of removing myself from my situation truly seemed a lot scarier than staying in it. i didn’t realize how good things could actually be because i was used to horrible conditions & that’s all i knew & experienced. the unknown was horrifying especially because i couldn’t control it. i wrote “weaning” after i had been facing everything head on & consistently dedicating months & months of mental effort into this unfamiliar chapter of healing. this song confirms it for me: the grass does grow greener if you let it. you’ll find yourself again & eventually feel safe enough to love again too, but this time with more love for yourself & a fuller cup to pour from. you’ll also realize how much shit you were tolerating & you’ll swear to yourself you’ll never tolerate it again. it’s a beautiful transformation that requires you to go through some ugly moments.
special thanks to @livvysalter for bringing this vision to life & for always providing a safe open space for me creatively & personally. liv filmed & photographed the visuals for this song & is a huge reason why i am happy to be alive🤍
